  "topic_name": "Human Nervous System and Sense Organs",
  "canonical_explanation": {
    "text": "The nervous system coordinates body activities through electrical impulses. Neurons (nerve cells) consist of cell body (soma), dendrites (receive impulses), and axon (transmit impulses). The CNS includes brain and spinal cord; PNS includes cranial (12 pairs) and spinal nerves (31 pairs). The brain has three main parts: cerebrum (thinking, memory, voluntary actions), cerebellum (balance, coordination), and medulla oblongata (involuntary actions like breathing). The autonomic nervous system has sympathetic (fight or flight) and parasympathetic (rest and digest) divisions. Reflex actions are quick, automatic responses via reflex arcs. The eye forms images through refraction by cornea and lens, with retina containing rods (dim light) and cones (color). The ear has three parts for hearing (external, middle, inner) with the cochlea for sound detection and vestibular apparatus for balance.",
    "rules": [
      "Neuron: cell body + dendrites + axon",
      "CNS: brain + spinal cord; PNS: cranial + spinal nerves",
      "Cerebrum: thinking, memory; Cerebellum: balance; Medulla: involuntary functions",
      "Reflex arc: receptor -> sensory neuron -> relay neuron -> motor neuron -> effector",
      "Autonomic NS: sympathetic (stress) + parasympathetic (relaxation)",
      "Eye: cornea, lens, retina (rods and cones), optic nerve",
      "Ear: external (pinna, canal), middle (ossicles), inner (cochlea, vestibular apparatus)"
    ]
  },
